proposals.synopsis:
A typical day in my classroom would look like a day of employment at McDonald&#039;s or Dunkin Donuts.  For that hands on training and experience students operate a bakery with delivery service to the faculty and staff. For 3 hours a day they serve up coffee, cookies, muffins, tea, lemonade and sandwiches. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;We live in a rural/suburban county in Central Florida where the poverty level is very high.  Students in my Exceptional Student Education (ESE) classes have a variety of disabilities (learning and physical) and receive employability training that will assist them in getting a job once they graduate from high school.  With the training they receive in this class, my students gain the experience needed to find a job outside of the classroom. 

Students are required to wear uniforms, punch a time clock, receive a paycheck (spendable in our classroom bakery) and are evaluated based on their performance.  In a given day we serve over 400 students, faculty, and staff! Where students were once unknown to the student body, they are now the most popular kids on campus. 

I teach the students to have high expectations of themselves and they can reach any goal they set out to achieve. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Our classroom is set up like a bakery, we are equipped with ovens to bake cookies, a microwave, fry pan, coffee machines, and refrigerator. We have a counter and a cash register. With the POS system, students will use the POS system for processing (taking) orders, simulating what they would use in places like McDonald&#039;s, Burger King, Publix, etc.  They are trained on how to count money, give back change and fulfill an order.  When they graduate, they will be able to list their training in this class as job experience. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Donations to this project will make a difference in a child&#039;s life by giving them the experience they need to be confident and a productive member of society.  They feel like they have the abilities and confidence to start life as adult without being totally dependent on their caregivers. &#034;Building confidence one student at a time.&#034;
